        "abstract": {
            "content": [
                {
                    "type": "paragraph", 
                    "text": "<i>bicoid</i> mRNA localises to the <i>Drosophila</i> oocyte anterior from stage 9 of oogenesis onwards to provide a local source for Bicoid protein for embryonic patterning. Live imaging at stage 9 reveals that <i>bicoid</i> mRNA particles undergo rapid Dynein-dependent movements near the oocyte anterior, but with no directional bias. Furthermore, <i>bicoid</i> mRNA localises normally in <i>shot</i><sup>2A2</sup>, which abolishes the polarised microtubule organisation. FRAP and photo-conversion experiments demonstrate that the RNA is stably anchored at the anterior, independently of microtubules. Thus, <i>bicoid</i> mRNA is localised by random active transport and anterior anchoring. Super-resolution imaging reveals that <i>bicoid</i> mRNA forms 110-120nm particles with variable RNA content, but constant size. These particles appear to be well-defined structures that package the RNA for transport and anchoring."
                }
            ]
        }
    }, 
